    <node id="Yes, there is a risk that continuously maintaining current standards without pushing for further development may not demonstrate enough ambition for the future. The education sector is continually evolving, with changes and different policies and priorities being implemented by successive governments. This can prevent the development of the sector if not managed properly. We are indeed in the midst of a significant period of change, with the new curriculum set to reach key stage 4 only in around seven years. The sheer amount of change in a relatively short period can put pressure on teachers, schools, colleges, and headteachers, requiring them to cope with these changes while avoiding excessive workloads. While it's crucial to balance the need for progress with the pressures on educators, it is also important to monitor and evaluate the implementation of new policies and practices to ensure their success." />
