    <node id="1. The national policy that encourages a pupil-led learning experience over traditional teaching methods is likely related to the foundation phase education implemented in Wales. This approach emphasizes developmental work and became compulsory for all schools from 2010 onwards. Meilyr Rowlands supports this policy because, when implemented properly, it has been shown to benefit pupils.&#10;&#10;However, he acknowledges that there may be a lack of understanding among headteachers regarding the principles of good pedagogy or good practice in about three quarters of schools. He attributes this issue to several factors, including:&#10;&#09;* A misunderstanding that less able children should receive grant support instead of more able but underachieving students.&#10;&#09;* The focus on improving exam results for underachieving pupils may inadvertently overlook the potential benefits of providing additional support to already achieving students.&#10;&#09;* Challenges in correctly identifying more able and talented pupils who could benefit from the grant.&#10;&#10;Meilyr Rowlands also points out that there is a lot of jargon around this approach, which might contribute to headteachers' difficulty in understanding it fully. To address this issue, they have produced substantial work explaining the technical terms and providing good examples of their implementation in practice." />
