    <node id="The Welsh Government's changes to performance measures in 2017 had a direct impact on the re-widening attainment gap between pupils on free school meals and those not on free school meals. The changes resulted in some examinations, qualifications, and courses that were typically followed by disadvantaged students no longer being part of headline performance indicators. This shift directly affected the performance assessment for schools with a higher proportion of such students, potentially exacerbating the attainment gap.&#10;&#10;There was also an indirect impact due to changes in funding allocation. The grant money initially intended for more able and talented pupils was being disproportionately spent on boys rather than girls from free school meal backgrounds. While there is room for discussion about the best definition of eligibility, schools have generally followed the spirit of the grant. However, this imbalance in funding distribution could potentially widen the attainment gap between disadvantaged and non-disadvantaged students indirectly.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Welsh Government's changes to performance measures in 2017 had both direct and indirect impacts on the re-widening attainment gap between pupils on free school meals and those not on free school meals. The immediate effect was a change in headline performance indicators, which affected schools with higher proportions of disadvantaged students. Indirectly, changes in grant allocation might have influenced funding distribution, potentially widening the attainment gap over time." />
    <node id=" might well be an indirect, longer-term impact as well. But, clearly, changing the performance indicators had a direct, immediate effect, because some of those examinations, qualifications, courses that were typically followed by this cohort of students weren't any longer part of the headline performance indicators. So, you've all heard about BTEC Science and the key skills qualifications. Those sorts of things that many of these pupils used to succeed at, and therefore get the performance indicator for the school, no longer count. So, it's had a direct impact, and it's one of the reasons why it's quite difficult to compare the results of one year and another, because of these changes in performance indicators.&#10;Speaker: Michelle Brown AM&#10;Content: Yes, that makes sense. Do you think there hasn't been any—? Can we take it from what you've said that there's been a positive improvement, or has it been negative?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: I think there's a growing realisation that secondary schools, key stage 4, is driven overly by performance indicators, and, whatever performance indicator you come up with, there will be unintended consequences. So, it's not, I think, useful to keep changing the performance" />
    <node id="Estyn has observed that schools have improved in targeted usage of the pupil development grant funding towards children eligible for free school meals compared to its initial implementation. However, there is still room for better targeting, as some schools interpret poverty more broadly and may not strictly adhere to the definition of free school meals when allocating resources. It is essential to refine the implementation of this approach while maintaining focus on the original target group, including potential adjustments for children who no longer receive free school meals but still require support." />
    <node id="Professor Donaldson was asked to undertake a review of Estyn's role due to the extensive education reforms and the need for external scrutiny in the current context of rapid educational changes. This was considered important because various aspects of work in the education system, including schools, colleges, and the system as a whole, have changed. The new education reforms require a careful balance between implementing changes and not overburdening teachers and headteachers with excessive workload pressure. Estyn's role in self-improvement adds to this responsibility, making external scrutiny particularly valuable for maintaining focus on continuous evolution and improvement." />
