    <node id=", I think it's a good thing to do at any given time, but considering the range and speed of change that we're facing in education now, I thought it was particularly important that we ask Graham Donaldson to look at the implications for our work of all this education reform.&#10;Speaker: Mark Reckless AM&#10;Content: What have been the biggest benefits to Wales of having Estyn as an independent body inspecting schools and other institutions in Wales compared to the work that Ofsted has done in England?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: Well, we have very good relationships with Ofsted and with Education Scotland and the Education Training Inspectorate in Northern Ireland. I wouldn't like to compare—I don't think it would be fair to compare ourselves. We do things slightly differently, but we benefit a lot from each other. We have inspectors from Ofsted or from Scotland, from Northern Ireland, on our inspections. We shadow them, and our inspectors go to their countries. So, we're working quite closely with the home countries, but also further afield with Holland and with the Republic of Ireland, for example. So, we're always, all of us, learning from one another about what we think they do well and" />
    <node id="1. The grant, being specifically for looked-after children, should ideally be used exclusively for their needs to ensure the targeted support they require is provided. This is supported by Mark Reckless AM and Meilyr Rowlands' views that the grant should primarily focus on looked-after children's educational requirements.&#10;2. However, using the grant to benefit vulnerable children who have more school transitions can be seen as a reasonable blurring of boundaries, considering such children might share similar needs with looked-after children. This approach is supported by EAS and acknowledged by Mark Reckless AM.&#10;3. It's essential to find an appropriate balance between maintaining the grant's specificity for looked-after children and using it to help other vulnerable groups with similar needs. To ensure this, schools need more information about the grant's objectives, as suggested by Julie Morgan AM and Meilyr Rowlands.&#10;4. In summary, while the grant should primarily focus on looked-after children, using it to support other vulnerable children facing similar challenges during school transitions can be an acceptable degree of blurring, provided there is clarity in communication and understanding about the grant's objectives and priorities." />
