    <node id="1. Schools may not fully comprehend the allocation and priorities of the PDG for looked-after and adopted children due to existing confusion about the grant's management, as it now goes to regional consortia instead of local authorities. This has led to uncertainty regarding how the grant is spent and what its priorities are, as mentioned by Meilyr Rowlands.&#10;2. The need for increased clarity and communication about the PDG objectives and target group (looked-after children) was emphasized during the conversation. Ensuring schools have a clear understanding of the grant's purpose and specificity is essential to provide looked-after children with the appropriate support they require." />
    <node id="1. Estyn benefits from close working relationships with other education inspectorates such as Ofsted (England), Education Scotland, and the Education Training Inspectorate in Northern Ireland. They learn from each other and have inspectors shadowing and being shadowed during inspections.&#10;2. One unique aspect of Estyn's approach to inspection is their use of nominee and peer inspectors. This involves having a member from the body being inspected as part of the inspection team, allowing them to understand the process and help their organization move forward after the inspection.&#10;3. This approach differs from Ofsted's methods since it incorporates those directly involved in the institution into the evaluation process, fostering better understanding and collaboration during the improvement process." />
    <node id="1. Enhance clarity and communication regarding the PDG objectives and target group: To ensure that schools have a clear understanding of the grant's purpose and specificity, it is essential to communicate effectively about the PDG's goals and target groups, particularly for looked-after children. This will help schools provide appropriate support for these students.&#10;&#10;2. Refine implementation and adhere to free school meals definition: Some schools interpret poverty more broadly when allocating resources, which may dilute the impact of the PDG on its intended beneficiaries. It is crucial to refine the implementation of this approach and maintain focus on the original target group – children eligible for free school meals – while considering potential adjustments for those who no longer receive free school meals but still require support.&#10;&#10;3. Increase attendance-focused initiatives: Although attendance has improved, there is still a significant gap between disadvantaged students and their peers. Schools should continue to prioritize attendance interventions using the PDG, as better attendance correlates strongly with better educational outcomes. This could include additional support services, counseling, or incentive programs to encourage regular school attendance.&#10;&#10;4. Monitor and evaluate PDG spending: Regularly assessing how the PDG is being used and its impact on attendance rates can help identify areas for improvement and ensure that resources are allocated effectively. This information should be shared with schools and regional consortia to promote best practices and continuous improvement.&#10;&#10;5. Consider more nuanced approaches: While using free school meal eligibility as a measure of disadvantage has been effective, there may be room for more refined methods. For example, offering continued support to students who have transitioned out of free school meals or incorporating other indicators of disadvantage could help provide a more comprehensive approach to supporting at-risk students." />
    <node id="'ve mentioned engagement with the curriculum. What more can be done?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: I think what's happening now is that people are targeting their attention on attendance. Attendance has improved in primary and in secondary generally. It has also improved for these cohorts as well, and at a faster rate than the rest of the cohort. So, there have been improvements. Nevertheless, I agree with you totally that it is a major, major problem, and that is why schools do use the PDG specifically to improve attendance.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: But you said they've not used it well enough.&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: Did I say that? They are using it, and attendance has improved, and the attendance of this cohort has improved more, but there's still a major, major problem. So, I think there needs to be even more attention—&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: So, what—? I'm looking for specifics. What can be done with the PDG?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: I think, as I said earlier, that these are major social issues." />
    <node id="1. The Association of Directors of Education in Wales (ADEW) and the Welsh Government have addressed the concern about insufficient training for senior leaders and middle managers by implementing residential courses run by the Staff College Wales. Last year, all serving directors attended these courses, and a 'Welsh future leaders in education' course was completed by 26 aspiring directors. Another cohort is being prepared for September 2018. These courses include external input from successful school heads and directors from Scotland to provide diverse perspectives and best practices.&#10;&#10;Source: Speaker Simon Brown, Strategic Director, Estyn&#10;&#10;Reference(s):&#10;- One of our concerns, apart from the fact that there was a large turnover of directors, was what sort of level of training senior leaders and middle managers were getting in those authorities.&#10;- Last year, all serving directors attended residential courses run by the Staff College Wales, facilitated by ADEW, and ADEW have just finished the first round of director—. The name of the course is the 'Welsh future leaders in education' course and 26 people have just finished that&#10;- They're putting in directors and chief executives from Scotland, they're putting in headteachers of very successful schools in England, who've got current grass-roots experience to share with these aspiring directors." />
    <node id="&#10;Speaker: Llyr Gruffydd AM&#10;Content: Thank you. I'd just like to spend a minute or two looking more specifically at post-16 education. The percentage of further education colleges who have reached a  good or better standard has increased, of course, over the past inspection cycle. I'd just like to ask what you think is responsible for that, and are there any lessons we can take out of that and transfer to other sectors within education?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: Thank you for the question, but I'm going to ask Simon to answer.&#10;Speaker: Simon Brown&#10;Content: As you're aware, the number of colleges from 22 to 12, and I think those mergers resulted in establishments that were stronger in terms of their leadership in particular. That leadership, I think the characteristics we have seen in the 'good' or 'better'—as you say, 80 per cent leadership good or better—has been a culture of openness, a culture of clarity of purpose about where the college is going. High staff morale has been maintained, because a number of those colleges—. Obviously, if you're merging large colleges as they did in north Wales, keeping staff morale high" />
    <node id="1. Over time, the targeting and use of the PDG have evolved to better address the underachievement of children who receive free school meals. Initially, funding was often spent on tackling underachievement generally rather than focusing specifically on those receiving free school meals. However, Estyn reports show improvement in targeted usage towards the intended beneficiaries (even though some schools may interpret poverty more broadly).&#10;&#10;2. Schools are utilizing this funding to improve pupil progress in various ways, such as tracking individual pupil progress, working with families and communities, and implementing extra-curricular activities that aim to boost student confidence and exam performance. For instance, a significant amount of funding is being spent on improving students' performance in key stage 4 exams.&#10;&#10;3. Attendance rates for disadvantaged students have seen some improvement due to the PDG; however, there is still a substantial gap between these students and their peers. Schools are employing attendance-focused initiatives using PDG funds, including additional support services, counseling, or incentive programs designed to encourage regular school attendance.&#10;&#10;4. Regular monitoring and evaluation of PDG spending can help identify areas for improvement and ensure effective resource allocation. Sharing this information with schools and regional consortia will promote best practices and continuous improvement in the use of PDG funds.&#10;&#10;5. While free school meal eligibility has been an effective measure of disadvantage, there may be room for more nuanced methods to support at-risk students further. These could include offering continued support to students who have transitioned out of free school meals or incorporating other indicators of disadvantage into the assessment process." />
    <node id="1. Estyn focuses on improving the performance of more able pupils in its inspections, making it a specific part of their inspection framework. They look at the relative performance of different groups, including more able pupils, and question schools about how they provide for these students.&#10;2. Meilyr Rowlands mentioned that new data being discussed, such as progress from year 6 tests, can help secondary schools identify more able children who may be underachieving, even if they are doing well overall.&#10;3. In response to a question about the Seren network and encouraging schools' engagement with it, Meilyr Rowlands suggested that Estyn will continue to look at the more able and talented stream and consider what more they can do through their inspection criteria and other means to encourage this from schools." />
