    <edge source="Using the measure of children eligible for free school meals is a good way to identify and target funding towards children from disadvantaged backgrounds, as there is a strong correlation between underachievement and this measure. However, there is room for improvement in fine-tuning the implementation of this approach. For instance, some have suggested that if a child has received free school meals for a certain period but no longer does, they may still need continued support. Additionally, it has been noted that schools interpret poverty in various ways and sometimes do not strictly adhere to the definition of free school meals, which can affect how funding is allocated. It could be beneficial to consider more nuanced approaches to defining and supporting disadvantaged backgrounds, while also maintaining a clear focus on the original target group." target="1. Mark Reckless AM and Michelle Brown AM hold a positive view of using the measure of children eligible for free school meals to identify and support children from disadvantaged backgrounds. They acknowledge that the implementation has improved over time, with better targeting towards the intended group. However, they recognize that challenges remain, including schools interpreting poverty in different ways when allocating resources.&#10;2. Meilyr Rowlands shares a consensus on using this measure's strengths but also suggests refining its application for more effectiveness. One suggestion is considering continued support for children who no longer receive free school meals but still need assistance, as there might be lingering effects of past disadvantage.&#10;3. Llyr Gruffydd AM appears to seek the panel's expert opinions on the use of this measure and whether it remains the best approach. The responses indicate that while the measure has merit in identifying disadvantaged children, fine-tuning is needed to ensure continued support for those who no longer receive free school meals but continue to require assistance.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, there is general agreement on using the measure of children eligible for free school meals as a way to identify and target funding towards disadvantaged backgrounds. To improve or fine-tune this approach, panel members suggest considering continued support for children who no longer receive free school meals but still need assistance, emphasizing that schools should strictly adhere to the definition of free school meals when allocating resources to minimize disparities.">
