    <edge source="Using the measure of children eligible for free school meals is a good way to identify and target funding towards children from disadvantaged backgrounds, as there is a strong correlation between underachievement and this measure. However, there is room for improvement in fine-tuning the implementation of this approach. For instance, some have suggested that if a child has received free school meals for a certain period but no longer does, they may still need continued support. Additionally, it has been noted that schools interpret poverty in various ways and sometimes do not strictly adhere to the definition of free school meals, which can affect how funding is allocated. It could be beneficial to consider more nuanced approaches to defining and supporting disadvantaged backgrounds, while also maintaining a clear focus on the original target group." target="1. Over time, the targeting and use of the PDG have evolved to better address the underachievement of children who receive free school meals. Initially, funding was often spent on tackling underachievement generally rather than focusing specifically on those receiving free school meals. However, Estyn reports show improvement in targeted usage towards the intended beneficiaries (even though some schools may interpret poverty more broadly).&#10;&#10;2. Schools are utilizing this funding to improve pupil progress in various ways, such as tracking individual pupil progress, working with families and communities, and implementing extra-curricular activities that aim to boost student confidence and exam performance. For instance, a significant amount of funding is being spent on improving students' performance in key stage 4 exams.&#10;&#10;3. Attendance rates for disadvantaged students have seen some improvement due to the PDG; however, there is still a substantial gap between these students and their peers. Schools are employing attendance-focused initiatives using PDG funds, including additional support services, counseling, or incentive programs designed to encourage regular school attendance.&#10;&#10;4. Regular monitoring and evaluation of PDG spending can help identify areas for improvement and ensure effective resource allocation. Sharing this information with schools and regional consortia will promote best practices and continuous improvement in the use of PDG funds.&#10;&#10;5. While free school meal eligibility has been an effective measure of disadvantage, there may be room for more nuanced methods to support at-risk students further. These could include offering continued support to students who have transitioned out of free school meals or incorporating other indicators of disadvantage into the assessment process.">
