    <edge source=".&#10;Speaker: Mark Reckless AM&#10;Content: Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Llyr Gruffydd AM&#10;Content: Just briefly, you touched earlier on using the measure of those who are eligible for free school meals as a way to identify children from disadvantaged backgrounds so that you can target this funding. Varied evidence has been given to us on this. Do you have an opinion on whether that's the best way?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: It certainly is a good way of doing it. There is a strong correlation between children who underachieve and that measure, so it is a strong measure. But, there is scope to discuss how exactly it does work. For example, some people say that if you have received free school meals for a period of time and now you're not receiving them, then perhaps you should still be receiving the funding for a period of time, for example. So, there are ways of fine-tuning that measure, I think. It's worth considering those approaches.&#10;Speaker: John Griffiths AM&#10;Content: Thanks for that. We move on now to Michelle.&#10;Speaker: Michelle Brown AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Good morning, everyone" target="The Welsh Government's changes to performance measures in 2017 had a direct impact on the re-widening attainment gap between pupils on free school meals and those not on free school meals. The changes resulted in some examinations, qualifications, and courses that were typically followed by disadvantaged students no longer being part of headline performance indicators. This shift directly affected the performance assessment for schools with a higher proportion of such students, potentially exacerbating the attainment gap.&#10;&#10;There was also an indirect impact due to changes in funding allocation. The grant money initially intended for more able and talented pupils was being disproportionately spent on boys rather than girls from free school meal backgrounds. While there is room for discussion about the best definition of eligibility, schools have generally followed the spirit of the grant. However, this imbalance in funding distribution could potentially widen the attainment gap between disadvantaged and non-disadvantaged students indirectly.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Welsh Government's changes to performance measures in 2017 had both direct and indirect impacts on the re-widening attainment gap between pupils on free school meals and those not on free school meals. The immediate effect was a change in headline performance indicators, which affected schools with higher proportions of disadvantaged students. Indirectly, changes in grant allocation might have influenced funding distribution, potentially widening the attainment gap over time.">
