    <edge source=".&#10;Speaker: Mark Reckless AM&#10;Content: Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Llyr Gruffydd AM&#10;Content: Just briefly, you touched earlier on using the measure of those who are eligible for free school meals as a way to identify children from disadvantaged backgrounds so that you can target this funding. Varied evidence has been given to us on this. Do you have an opinion on whether that's the best way?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: It certainly is a good way of doing it. There is a strong correlation between children who underachieve and that measure, so it is a strong measure. But, there is scope to discuss how exactly it does work. For example, some people say that if you have received free school meals for a period of time and now you're not receiving them, then perhaps you should still be receiving the funding for a period of time, for example. So, there are ways of fine-tuning that measure, I think. It's worth considering those approaches.&#10;Speaker: John Griffiths AM&#10;Content: Thanks for that. We move on now to Michelle.&#10;Speaker: Michelle Brown AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Good morning, everyone" target="1. Mark Reckless AM and Michelle Brown AM hold a positive view of using the measure of children eligible for free school meals to identify and support children from disadvantaged backgrounds. They acknowledge that the implementation has improved over time, with better targeting towards the intended group. However, they recognize that challenges remain, including schools interpreting poverty in different ways when allocating resources.&#10;2. Meilyr Rowlands shares a consensus on using this measure's strengths but also suggests refining its application for more effectiveness. One suggestion is considering continued support for children who no longer receive free school meals but still need assistance, as there might be lingering effects of past disadvantage.&#10;3. Llyr Gruffydd AM appears to seek the panel's expert opinions on the use of this measure and whether it remains the best approach. The responses indicate that while the measure has merit in identifying disadvantaged children, fine-tuning is needed to ensure continued support for those who no longer receive free school meals but continue to require assistance.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, there is general agreement on using the measure of children eligible for free school meals as a way to identify and target funding towards disadvantaged backgrounds. To improve or fine-tune this approach, panel members suggest considering continued support for children who no longer receive free school meals but still need assistance, emphasizing that schools should strictly adhere to the definition of free school meals when allocating resources to minimize disparities.">
