    <edge source=" This grant has been targeted far better by now than it was originally. Estyn has made several reports regarding the effectiveness of the grant, and, really, going back to before this specific grant, to a similar grant, called RAISE. At the start of this grant, the funding was often spent on tackling underachievement, rather than dealing with the underachievement of children who are eligible for free school meals specifically. But, over a period of time, we have seen that it is targeted much better by now. That's not to say that the targeting is working perfectly still, and I think that we are seeing examples where the targeting isn't going just to children who receive free school meals. Schools sometimes interpret poverty in a slightly wider way than that. In terms of what schools are doing with the grant, we have given evidence to you of the kinds of things that they are doing. They are tracking progress of pupils, they are trying to improve attendance, they are trying to work with families and the community in general, they're doing work specifically to improve how children are doing in exams, in key stage 4, specifically—a lot of funding is being spent on that—improving the confidence of students, taking students on extra-curricular activities" target="1. Over time, the targeting and use of the PDG have evolved to better address the underachievement of children who receive free school meals. Initially, funding was often spent on tackling underachievement generally rather than focusing specifically on those receiving free school meals. However, Estyn reports show improvement in targeted usage towards the intended beneficiaries (even though some schools may interpret poverty more broadly).&#10;&#10;2. Schools are utilizing this funding to improve pupil progress in various ways, such as tracking individual pupil progress, working with families and communities, and implementing extra-curricular activities that aim to boost student confidence and exam performance. For instance, a significant amount of funding is being spent on improving students' performance in key stage 4 exams.&#10;&#10;3. Attendance rates for disadvantaged students have seen some improvement due to the PDG; however, there is still a substantial gap between these students and their peers. Schools are employing attendance-focused initiatives using PDG funds, including additional support services, counseling, or incentive programs designed to encourage regular school attendance.&#10;&#10;4. Regular monitoring and evaluation of PDG spending can help identify areas for improvement and ensure effective resource allocation. Sharing this information with schools and regional consortia will promote best practices and continuous improvement in the use of PDG funds.&#10;&#10;5. While free school meal eligibility has been an effective measure of disadvantage, there may be room for more nuanced methods to support at-risk students further. These could include offering continued support to students who have transitioned out of free school meals or incorporating other indicators of disadvantage into the assessment process.">
