    <edge source=" what we're saying is that headteachers are not necessarily understanding it. I think there is quite a lot of jargon around it. I was just looking in the annual report. Quite unusually, in this section, we have had to actually explain some of the technical terms, like 'continuous provision'. So that's, I think, one of the reasons why people don't understand it fully. That's why we did produce this quite substantial bit of work, trying to unpack what this actually means in practice and giving a lot of good examples of the practice.&#10;Speaker: Mark Reckless AM&#10;Content: You referred to evidence of this approach working. Given the timing of when it was brought in and where we are now, has that really had time to distil through the system and give compelling evidence that this approach works better than more traditional approaches?&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: I think it has, to be fair. I think this has, because we're talking about a lot of developmental work related to the foundation phase prior to 2010, but it became compulsory for all schools to deliver it from 2010 onwards. So, that gives enough time for children to have been through the whole of the foundation phase onto key stage" target="1. Examples of improper implementation of the foundation phase: The transcript does not provide specific examples of how the foundation phase is not being implemented in its true spirit in most schools. However, it mentions that some schools have reverted to more traditional methods, especially in Year 1 and Year 2, after the introduction of new tests. This suggests that these schools may be focusing more on formal teaching methods and test preparation rather than fostering a learning environment that encourages children's self-directed choices and continuous provision.&#10;&#10;2. Reversion to traditional methods: Some schools have reverted to traditional methods due to the pressure of new tests. After the introduction of new tests, these schools may prioritize structured teaching and test preparation over the foundation phase's pedagogical approach. This shift could be because traditional methods are perceived to produce better results in standardized testing, or teachers and administrators might feel more comfortable with familiar teaching practices.&#10;&#10;It is essential to note that the transcript does not offer specific examples of this behavior; therefore, further investigation would be required to identify particular instances where schools have reverted to traditional methods.">
