    <edge source="1. The PDG has had some positive impact on attendance rates of students eligible for free school meals at key stage 4, as there has been a correlation between the grant's implementation and a slight improvement in attendance. However, the transcript suggests that there is still a significant gap between the attendance rates of disadvantaged students and their peers (35% vs 60% attending 95% of the time).&#10;   1. Meilyr Rowlands mentions that things are being done and money is being spent through the PDG, but it is challenging to directly attribute improvements or lack thereof to the grant due to the complexity of factors influencing attendance and educational outcomes." target="1. Schools may not fully comprehend the allocation and priorities of the PDG for looked-after and adopted children due to existing confusion about the grant's management, as it now goes to regional consortia instead of local authorities. This has led to uncertainty regarding how the grant is spent and what its priorities are, as mentioned by Meilyr Rowlands.&#10;2. The need for increased clarity and communication about the PDG objectives and target group (looked-after children) was emphasized during the conversation. Ensuring schools have a clear understanding of the grant's purpose and specificity is essential to provide looked-after children with the appropriate support they require.">
