    </edge>
    <edge source="1. The committee will be discussing Estyn's (the education and training inspectorate for Wales) annual report for 2016-17 during this session. They will cover various areas identified in the agenda, raising issues they think appropriate.&#10;2. The witnesses present for this session are Meilyr Rowlands (Chief Inspector), Claire Morgan (Strategic Director), and Simon Brown (Strategic Director) from Estyn." target="1. The Association of Directors of Education in Wales (ADEW) and the Welsh Government have addressed the concern about insufficient training for senior leaders and middle managers by implementing residential courses run by the Staff College Wales. Last year, all serving directors attended these courses, and a 'Welsh future leaders in education' course was completed by 26 aspiring directors. Another cohort is being prepared for September 2018. These courses include external input from successful school heads and directors from Scotland to provide diverse perspectives and best practices.&#10;&#10;Source: Speaker Simon Brown, Strategic Director, Estyn&#10;&#10;Reference(s):&#10;- One of our concerns, apart from the fact that there was a large turnover of directors, was what sort of level of training senior leaders and middle managers were getting in those authorities.&#10;- Last year, all serving directors attended residential courses run by the Staff College Wales, facilitated by ADEW, and ADEW have just finished the first round of director—. The name of the course is the 'Welsh future leaders in education' course and 26 people have just finished that&#10;- They're putting in directors and chief executives from Scotland, they're putting in headteachers of very successful schools in England, who've got current grass-roots experience to share with these aspiring directors.">
