    <edge source="1. The committee will be discussing Estyn's (the education and training inspectorate for Wales) annual report for 2016-17 during this session. They will cover various areas identified in the agenda, raising issues they think appropriate.&#10;2. The witnesses present for this session are Meilyr Rowlands (Chief Inspector), Claire Morgan (Strategic Director), and Simon Brown (Strategic Director) from Estyn." target="Involving parents and community leaders in improving school attendance for a specific group of pupils is crucial, as it helps to address issues that are outside of the school's control. When headteachers consider themselves community leaders and engage directly with families of disadvantaged or underachieving children, they build strong relationships and create an environment where the school can collaborate with external agencies to tackle barriers to attendance.&#10;&#10;Cefn Hengoed School serves as a good example of progress made in this area. They have set up arrangements that engage directly with families, striving to understand and remove barriers to learning for disadvantaged learners. The PDG (Pupil Deprivation Grant) is used to appoint staff who facilitate these arrangements, providing one-to-one support, monitoring attendance, visiting homes, and bringing agencies into the school to address issues that impact attendance.&#10;&#10;By engaging with the community and families, Cefn Hengoed School has been able to make significant progress in improving attendance for their targeted group of pupils. Their success lies in addressing barriers to learning specific to their students, developing a strong relationship with families, and coordinating efforts with external agencies when necessary.">
