    <edge source="The Welsh Government's changes to performance measures in 2017 had a direct impact on the re-widening attainment gap between pupils on free school meals and those not on free school meals. The changes resulted in some examinations, qualifications, and courses that were typically followed by disadvantaged students no longer being part of headline performance indicators. This shift directly affected the performance assessment for schools with a higher proportion of such students, potentially exacerbating the attainment gap.&#10;&#10;There was also an indirect impact due to changes in funding allocation. The grant money initially intended for more able and talented pupils was being disproportionately spent on boys rather than girls from free school meal backgrounds. While there is room for discussion about the best definition of eligibility, schools have generally followed the spirit of the grant. However, this imbalance in funding distribution could potentially widen the attainment gap between disadvantaged and non-disadvantaged students indirectly.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Welsh Government's changes to performance measures in 2017 had both direct and indirect impacts on the re-widening attainment gap between pupils on free school meals and those not on free school meals. The immediate effect was a change in headline performance indicators, which affected schools with higher proportions of disadvantaged students. Indirectly, changes in grant allocation might have influenced funding distribution, potentially widening the attainment gap over time." target="1. Mark Reckless AM and Michelle Brown AM hold a positive view of using the measure of children eligible for free school meals to identify and support children from disadvantaged backgrounds. They acknowledge that the implementation has improved over time, with better targeting towards the intended group. However, they recognize that challenges remain, including schools interpreting poverty in different ways when allocating resources.&#10;2. Meilyr Rowlands shares a consensus on using this measure's strengths but also suggests refining its application for more effectiveness. One suggestion is considering continued support for children who no longer receive free school meals but still need assistance, as there might be lingering effects of past disadvantage.&#10;3. Llyr Gruffydd AM appears to seek the panel's expert opinions on the use of this measure and whether it remains the best approach. The responses indicate that while the measure has merit in identifying disadvantaged children, fine-tuning is needed to ensure continued support for those who no longer receive free school meals but continue to require assistance.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, there is general agreement on using the measure of children eligible for free school meals as a way to identify and target funding towards disadvantaged backgrounds. To improve or fine-tune this approach, panel members suggest considering continued support for children who no longer receive free school meals but still need assistance, emphasizing that schools should strictly adhere to the definition of free school meals when allocating resources to minimize disparities.">
