    <edge source="The Welsh Government's changes to performance measures in 2017 had a direct impact on the re-widening attainment gap between pupils on free school meals and those not on free school meals. The changes resulted in some examinations, qualifications, and courses that were typically followed by disadvantaged students no longer being part of headline performance indicators. This shift directly affected the performance assessment for schools with a higher proportion of such students, potentially exacerbating the attainment gap.&#10;&#10;There was also an indirect impact due to changes in funding allocation. The grant money initially intended for more able and talented pupils was being disproportionately spent on boys rather than girls from free school meal backgrounds. While there is room for discussion about the best definition of eligibility, schools have generally followed the spirit of the grant. However, this imbalance in funding distribution could potentially widen the attainment gap between disadvantaged and non-disadvantaged students indirectly.&#10;&#10;In summary, the Welsh Government's changes to performance measures in 2017 had both direct and indirect impacts on the re-widening attainment gap between pupils on free school meals and those not on free school meals. The immediate effect was a change in headline performance indicators, which affected schools with higher proportions of disadvantaged students. Indirectly, changes in grant allocation might have influenced funding distribution, potentially widening the attainment gap over time." target="1. Over time, the targeting and use of the PDG have evolved to better address the underachievement of children who receive free school meals. Initially, funding was often spent on tackling underachievement generally rather than focusing specifically on those receiving free school meals. However, Estyn reports show improvement in targeted usage towards the intended beneficiaries (even though some schools may interpret poverty more broadly).&#10;&#10;2. Schools are utilizing this funding to improve pupil progress in various ways, such as tracking individual pupil progress, working with families and communities, and implementing extra-curricular activities that aim to boost student confidence and exam performance. For instance, a significant amount of funding is being spent on improving students' performance in key stage 4 exams.&#10;&#10;3. Attendance rates for disadvantaged students have seen some improvement due to the PDG; however, there is still a substantial gap between these students and their peers. Schools are employing attendance-focused initiatives using PDG funds, including additional support services, counseling, or incentive programs designed to encourage regular school attendance.&#10;&#10;4. Regular monitoring and evaluation of PDG spending can help identify areas for improvement and ensure effective resource allocation. Sharing this information with schools and regional consortia will promote best practices and continuous improvement in the use of PDG funds.&#10;&#10;5. While free school meal eligibility has been an effective measure of disadvantage, there may be room for more nuanced methods to support at-risk students further. These could include offering continued support to students who have transitioned out of free school meals or incorporating other indicators of disadvantage into the assessment process.">
