    <edge source="Professor Donaldson was asked to undertake a review of Estyn's role due to the extensive education reforms and the need for external scrutiny in the current context of rapid educational changes. This was considered important because various aspects of work in the education system, including schools, colleges, and the system as a whole, have changed. The new education reforms require a careful balance between implementing changes and not overburdening teachers and headteachers with excessive workload pressure. Estyn's role in self-improvement adds to this responsibility, making external scrutiny particularly valuable for maintaining focus on continuous evolution and improvement." target="1. Estyn focuses on improving the performance of more able pupils in its inspections, making it a specific part of their inspection framework. They look at the relative performance of different groups, including more able pupils, and question schools about how they provide for these students.&#10;2. Meilyr Rowlands mentioned that new data being discussed, such as progress from year 6 tests, can help secondary schools identify more able children who may be underachieving, even if they are doing well overall.&#10;3. In response to a question about the Seren network and encouraging schools' engagement with it, Meilyr Rowlands suggested that Estyn will continue to look at the more able and talented stream and consider what more they can do through their inspection criteria and other means to encourage this from schools.">
