    <edge source="1. Examples of improper implementation of the foundation phase: The transcript does not provide specific examples of how the foundation phase is not being implemented in its true spirit in most schools. However, it mentions that some schools have reverted to more traditional methods, especially in Year 1 and Year 2, after the introduction of new tests. This suggests that these schools may be focusing more on formal teaching methods and test preparation rather than fostering a learning environment that encourages children's self-directed choices and continuous provision.&#10;&#10;2. Reversion to traditional methods: Some schools have reverted to traditional methods due to the pressure of new tests. After the introduction of new tests, these schools may prioritize structured teaching and test preparation over the foundation phase's pedagogical approach. This shift could be because traditional methods are perceived to produce better results in standardized testing, or teachers and administrators might feel more comfortable with familiar teaching practices.&#10;&#10;It is essential to note that the transcript does not offer specific examples of this behavior; therefore, further investigation would be required to identify particular instances where schools have reverted to traditional methods." target=" a challenge that we haven't cracked yet in Wales: how do we make sure that good practice does travel? I think one specifically for foundation phase is a good idea, because we've got a specific issue with the foundation phase.&#10;Speaker: Mark Reckless AM&#10;Content: When you say that—&#10;Speaker: John Griffiths AM&#10;Content: Mark, just before you go on, I think Julie wanted to come in on this point as well.&#10;Speaker: Julie Morgan AM&#10;Content: Yes. I just wondered if you could give us some examples about how the foundation phase is not being implemented in the true spirit of the foundation phase in the three quarters of schools that you think fall—.&#10;Speaker: Meilyr Rowlands&#10;Content: Well, what we mean by that is schools not necessarily teaching badly, but in a more traditional way. And where we've seen that most obviously is in year 1 and year 2. Some schools actually reverted, after the introduction of the new tests, from what was pedagogy that was in line with the foundation phase. And basically, if I understand it correctly, it's more to do with the children making their own choices about what they do. And that is pretty">
