    <edge source="1. Collaboration and shared learning: Schools can engage in collaboration and share best practices with other organizations involved in school-to-school support. This enables them to learn from one another's experiences and identify effective strategies tailored to their specific contexts.&#10;&#10;2. Effective resource allocation: Strong strategic leadership can help schools allocate resources more effectively, ensuring that support is provided to the right students at the right time. By focusing on the individual-targeted nature of grants like the PDG, schools can help ensure that funding reaches those most in need and address potential gaps in awareness or understanding about the grant's targeting.&#10;&#10;3. Data-driven decision-making: Strong strategic leadership can foster a culture of continuous improvement and data-driven decision-making, enabling schools to monitor progress and adjust their strategies accordingly. Regularly evaluating the impact of various strategies on attendance and exclusion rates for disadvantaged students helps schools make informed decisions about resource allocation and other factors that contribute to student success.&#10;&#10;4. Engaging families and communities: Schools can engage with families and the community to address barriers to learning, especially in cases where families have had negative experiences with education themselves. Activities like Families at Brackla in Bridgend or Cefn Hengoed's extensive strategy for engaging with the community can help equip children from disadvantaged backgrounds to participate in decisions around the curriculum and become more confident learners.&#10;&#10;5. Proactive liaison with agencies: School leaders can act as community leaders, building strong relationships with families of disadvantaged children or underachieving students. This enables schools to either liaise with different agencies or bring agencies into the school to address issues that are outside school control, ensuring that students receive necessary support beyond the classroom.&#10;&#10;6. One-to-one support: Schools can use resources like the PDG to appoint staff whose role is to facilitate one-to-one support for disadvantaged children, monitor attendance, and visit homes where children are not coming into schools. This allows schools to address barriers that prevent students from attending class and provide individualized support.&#10;&#10;7. Continued support: Schools should consider continued support for students who may no longer receive free school meals but still require assistance. Additionally, schools can refine their implementation of strategies targeting children eligible for free school meals by considering more nuanced approaches to defining and supporting disadvantaged backgrounds while maintaining a clear focus on the original target group." target=" numeracy support, tracking pupils—all those sorts of things. But an important element of this, I think, is engaging with the learners, but also with parents and the community. I think what we've found is that the most effective schools—the ones that really do make a big difference to this cohort of students—are the ones that do that most effectively.&#10;Speaker: Claire Morgan&#10;Content: I think that there are different situations in different schools, but in the best schools, they evaluate the barriers to learning for their particular children. Often we see that engagement with communities is part of that engagement with families. In Brackla Primary School, in Bridgend, they've got Families at Brackla, and it's a range of activities to engage with families. Families often have had a negative experience of education themselves, and the schools are trying to address some of those concerns. Cefn Hengoed in Swansea, which I'm sure many of you know about, have had an extensive strategy for engaging with the community, with the families, and equipping their children to participate in decisions around the curriculum, making them more confident learners. So, it is about removing the barriers for disadvantaged learners.&#10;Speaker: Michelle Brown AM">
