    <edge source="1. The current tracking system for previously looked-after children who have since been adopted is not very targeted, as the pupil-level annual school census (PLASC) data does not differentiate whether children are adopted or not. This makes it difficult to track adopted children effectively. However, looked-after children are being tracked by regional consortia.&#10;2. The discussion reveals that there might be a lack of clarity regarding the use of a specific grant for looked-after children who have since been adopted, as opposed to all adopted children. This confusion needs to be addressed directly with the Welsh Government for clarification.&#10;3. While there is room for improvement in tracking previously looked-after children who have been adopted, it is crucial to ensure that any grant specifically targeting looked-after children is used appropriately and effectively to address their unique educational needs." target="1. Schools may not fully comprehend the allocation and priorities of the PDG for looked-after and adopted children due to existing confusion about the grant's management, as it now goes to regional consortia instead of local authorities. This has led to uncertainty regarding how the grant is spent and what its priorities are, as mentioned by Meilyr Rowlands.&#10;2. The need for increased clarity and communication about the PDG objectives and target group (looked-after children) was emphasized during the conversation. Ensuring schools have a clear understanding of the grant's purpose and specificity is essential to provide looked-after children with the appropriate support they require.">
