    <edge source="1. Estyn benefits from close working relationships with other education inspectorates such as Ofsted (England), Education Scotland, and the Education Training Inspectorate in Northern Ireland. They learn from each other and have inspectors shadowing and being shadowed during inspections.&#10;2. One unique aspect of Estyn's approach to inspection is their use of nominee and peer inspectors. This involves having a member from the body being inspected as part of the inspection team, allowing them to understand the process and help their organization move forward after the inspection.&#10;3. This approach differs from Ofsted's methods since it incorporates those directly involved in the institution into the evaluation process, fostering better understanding and collaboration during the improvement process." target="1. Estyn focuses on improving the performance of more able pupils in its inspections, making it a specific part of their inspection framework. They look at the relative performance of different groups, including more able pupils, and question schools about how they provide for these students.&#10;2. Meilyr Rowlands mentioned that new data being discussed, such as progress from year 6 tests, can help secondary schools identify more able children who may be underachieving, even if they are doing well overall.&#10;3. In response to a question about the Seren network and encouraging schools' engagement with it, Meilyr Rowlands suggested that Estyn will continue to look at the more able and talented stream and consider what more they can do through their inspection criteria and other means to encourage this from schools.">
